The fetishists of free trade
CAMBRIDGE – I was recently invited to guest lecture in Harvard colleague Joseph Nye’s course on globalization. “I must warn you.”
One of them warned me in advance that these students are strong proponents of globalization.
He asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and more than 90 percent favored the former.
And still before the magic effects of teaching comparative advantage.
We know that using the same questions on a representative sample – rather than Harvard students – in a real survey would yield a starkly different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents of trade restrictions to supporters is 2:1.
But the answers given by Harvard students would not come as particularly surprising.
Because those with higher技术水平和更好教育背景的人通常比蓝领工人更倾向于支持自由贸易。   To make it sound more natural in English, you could say: Because people with higher technical skills and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
Perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their future (and financial) prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they actually don't understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same questions in a different form to emphasize the distributional effects that trade might generate.
The consensus in favor of fair trade has disappeared almost more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I asked everyone if they agreed that I should start with a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers and then told them I had a way to make the $200 disappear from Nicholas's account—poof!—while simultaneously adding $300 to John's account. The grand feat of social engineering could add an extra $100 value to the class as a whole.
Will they allow me to pull off this little trick?
Only a small portion vehemently agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed implementing this transformation.
Sure, please provide the Chinese sentence that you would like me to translate into English.
It is clear that students find it difficult to tolerate such a large-scale income redistribution, even in a situation where the size of the economic pie has grown.
I then asked why most of them seemed almost instinctively to support free trade, even though free trade actually leads to a similar, and in fact even more pronounced, redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students all seemed to be stunned.
I continued, let's assume that Nicholas and John both have competing small companies.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products, leaving him not only $300 ahead of Nicolas but also driving Nicolas’s company out of the market and causing a $200 loss for him.
So how many students endorse this shift?
Most of the votes were in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis that is directly related to international trade.
Is John挤outing Nicholas from the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?   Note: "挤出市场" literally means "squeeze out of the market," but in the context of business competition, it's more commonly expressed as "挤out from the market." The translation assumes that "尼古拉斯" (Nicholas) is a company or competitor and "约翰" (John) is also a company or individual engaging in competitive practices. If there's more specific context, please provide for further refinement.
Or outsource business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet adequately protected?
Or employing child labor in Indonesia?
The degree of agreement with this shift then decreases sequentially with the above options.
Moreover, technological innovations will also put some people at a more disadvantaged position like trade does, what is your stance on this?
Only a few students are willing to restrain the development of technology.
For almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs in order to preserve candle-makers' jobs is a stupid idea.
Therefore, what students oppose is not necessarily redistribution, but certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they are concerned about the fairness of the procedure.
To make a judgment about the outcomes of redistribution, we must know the objective context that produced these results.
We do not resent Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their competitors have had it tough for a long time, which may be because they and their rivals operate according to the same basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
If Gates and Buffett had become wealthy not through their own intelligence and effort, but through fraud, violating labor laws, destroying the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be very different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved through violations of widely accepted moral standards within our own country, what justification do we have to be comfortable with it when it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to achieve equality over the long term and anticipate that everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to be less concerned about the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that it is crucial to promote technological development despite its potential for bringing short-term negative impacts on certain individuals.
On the other hand, when trade continually impacts the same group of people – low-educated blue-collar workers – we become worried about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute the worries about globalization to foolishly selfish trade protectionist motivations or ignorance, without realizing that the most pressing issue is actually one of morality.
Due to their inability to recognize that international trade sometimes – of course, not often – leads to redistribution outcomes that we find unacceptable domestically, these economists also fail to intervene appropriately in public debates.
And since their arguments on moral grounds are untenable, how can they defend trade vigorously?
When globalization occasionally triggers a thorny issue related to the legalization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons to be carefully balanced, including the possibility that globalization may result in a more severe deprivation of wealth for people in other places than for victims within the United States itself.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion about this and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions.
And the obsession with globalization solely because it has made the pie bigger will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long term.
